<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2016, total product gross profit was $371.2&nbsp;million, down $82.8&nbsp;million, or 18.2%, versus
	fiscal 2015, as the impact of slightly higher home heating oil and propane margins ($4.8 million) and an increase in gross profit from other petroleum products ($1.2 million) was more than offset by a decline in home heating oil and propane volume
	($88.8 million).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Cost of Installations and Services
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Total installation costs for fiscal 2016 increased by $2.7&nbsp;million, or 3.7%, to $75.9&nbsp;million, compared to $73.2&nbsp;million in
	installation costs for fiscal 2015, due to acquisitions and some growth in the base business. Installation costs as a percentage of installation sales for fiscal 2016 and fiscal 2015 were 83.7% and 84.2%, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Service expenses increased slightly to $153.1&nbsp;million for fiscal 2016, or 95.9% of service sales, versus $152.8&nbsp;million, or 98.1% of
	service sales, for fiscal 2015, as the additional service expense related to acquisitions of $4.4&nbsp;million was almost totally offset by a reduction in the base business of $4.0&nbsp;million. During fiscal 2015, temperatures were much colder than
	normal and drove an increase in the number of service hours required to ensure customers&#146; heating systems were operational. By contrast the mild weather experienced during fiscal 2016 did not require a similar level of service and, as a result,
	expenses were lower. We realized a
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	31
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage32"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	combined gross profit from service and installation of $21.3&nbsp;million for fiscal 2016 compared to a combined gross profit of $16.7&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015. Management views the service
	and installation department on a combined basis because many overhead functions and direct expenses such as service technician time cannot be separated or precisely allocated to either service or installation billings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	(Increase) Decrease in the Fair Value of Derivative Instruments
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During fiscal 2016, the change in the fair value of derivative instruments resulted in a $18.2&nbsp;million credit due to the expiration of
	certain hedged positions (a $15.3&nbsp;million credit) and an increase in the market value for unexpired hedges (a $2.9&nbsp;million credit).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During fiscal 2015, the change in the fair value of derivative instruments resulted in a $4.2&nbsp;million charge due to the expiration of
	certain hedged positions (a $12.1&nbsp;million credit) and a decrease in the market value of unexpired hedges (a $16.3&nbsp;million charge).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Delivery
	and Branch Expenses
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2016, delivery and branch expenses decreased $32.5&nbsp;million, or 10.5%, to $276.5&nbsp;million,
	compared to $309.0&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015, as an acquisition related increase of $10.4&nbsp;million was more than offset by lower delivery and branch expenses of $42.9&nbsp;million, or 13.9%, largely due to the weather related decline in home
	heating oil and propane volume in the base business of 24.9%, lower bad debt expense of $4.3&nbsp;million, and a $12.5&nbsp;million credit recorded in the first quarter of fiscal 2016 under the Partnership&#146;s weather hedge contract.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Depreciation and Amortization
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal
	2016, depreciation and amortization expense increased by $1.6&nbsp;million, or 6.4%, to $26.5&nbsp;million, compared to $24.9&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015, due to acquisitions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	General and Administrative Expenses
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For
	fiscal 2016, general and administrative expenses decreased $2.5&nbsp;million, to $23.4&nbsp;million, from $25.9&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015, primarily due to a reduction in profit sharing. The Partnership accrues approximately 6% of Adjusted
	EBITDA, as defined in the profit sharing plan, for distribution to its employees, and this amount is payable when the Partnership achieves Adjusted EBITDA of at least 70% of the amount budgeted. The dollar amount of the profit sharing pool is
	subject to increases and decreases in line with increases and decreases in Adjusted EBITDA.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Multiemployer Pension Plan Withdrawal Charge
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In fiscal 2015, we entered into an agreement among certain Star subsidiaries and the New England Teamsters and Trucking Industry Pension Fund
	(the &#147;NETTI Fund&#148;), a multiemployer pension plan in which such Star subsidiaries participate, providing for Star&#146;s participating subsidiaries to withdraw from the NETTI Fund&#146;s original employer pool and enter the NETTI
	Fund&#146;s new employer pool. The withdrawal from the original employer pool triggered an undiscounted withdrawal obligation of $48.0&nbsp;million to be paid in equal monthly installments over 30 years, or $1.6&nbsp;million per year. The estimated
	annual
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	after-tax
</FONT>
	cash impact of entering into this agreement is $0.9&nbsp;million. In September 2015, we recorded a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	charge in order to establish a withdrawal
	obligation of approximately $17.8&nbsp;million on the consolidated balance sheet, representing the present value of the $48.0&nbsp;million of future payment obligation at a discount rate of 8.22%. We also recorded a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	deferred tax benefit from the agreement of approximately $7.0&nbsp;million. We believe the new agreement reduces long-term financial risk for the Partnership. This 2015 expense is
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-recurring.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Finance Charge Income
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2016, finance charge income decreased by $1.7&nbsp;million, or 35.3%, to $3.1&nbsp;million compared to $4.8&nbsp;million for fiscal
	2015. The decline in the wholesale cost of product and the decline in volume sold led to lower product sales and thus a decline in accounts receivable balances subject to a finance charge.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	32
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage33"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Interest Expense, Net
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2016, interest expense decreased $6.6&nbsp;million, or 46.8%, to $7.5&nbsp;million compared to $14.1&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015.
	In September 2015, the Partnership redeemed its $125.0&nbsp;million principal amount of 8.875% Senior Notes outstanding due 2017 with proceeds from a new, five year $100.0&nbsp;million bank term-loan and cash. This refinancing drove the reduction in
	interest expense due to lower variable rates and lower principal outstanding.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Amortization of Debt Issuance Costs
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2016, amortization of debt issuance costs decreased $0.6&nbsp;million to $1.2&nbsp;million compared to $1.8&nbsp;million for fiscal
	2015. The refinancing of the Partnership&#146;s 8.875% Senior Notes with the bank term-loan resulted in a lower level of deferred charges to be written off.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Loss on Debt Redemption of Debt
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In
	September 2015, the Partnership redeemed all of its $125.0&nbsp;million principal amount of 8.875% Senior Notes due 2017, at the then current redemption price of $104.438 per $100 of principal plus accrued interest. The Partnership recorded a loss
	of $7.3&nbsp;million on this transaction, resulting from the $5.5&nbsp;million redemption price premium, the related write-offs of $1.5&nbsp;million in unamortized deferred charges and $0.3&nbsp;million of unamortized debt discount. This expense is
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-recurring
</FONT>
	in fiscal 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Income Tax Expense
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2016, the Partnership&#146;s income tax expense increased by $0.9&nbsp;million to $33.7&nbsp;million, from $32.8&nbsp;million for
	fiscal 2015, primarily due to an increase in income before income taxes of $8.3&nbsp;million, partially offset by a reduction in the effective income tax rate. The Partnership&#146;s effective income tax rate was 42.9% for fiscal 2016, compared to
	46.6&nbsp;% for fiscal 2015. In fiscal 2015, the loss on the redemption of the Partnership&#146;s $125.0&nbsp;million principal amount of 8.875% Senior Notes due 2017 was not deductible at the Partnership&#146;s corporate subsidiaries which caused
	an increase in the effective tax rate for that year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Net Income
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2016, net income increased $7.4&nbsp;million, or 19.6%, to $44.9&nbsp;million, from $37.6&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015, primarily
	due to an increase in pretax profit of $8.3&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Adjusted EBITDA
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2016, Adjusted EBITDA decreased by $44.8&nbsp;million, or 31.9%, to $95.7&nbsp;million as the impact of slightly higher home heating
	oil and propane per gallon margins, lower operating expenses in the base business, lower service and installation costs and the $12.5&nbsp;million credit recorded in the first quarter of 2016 under the weather insurance contract were more than
	offset by the impact of the decline in volume attributable to the 21.6% warmer weather and net customer attrition for fiscal 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	EBITDA
	and Adjusted EBITDA should not be considered as an alternative to net income (as an indicator of operating performance) or as an alternative to cash flow (as a measure of liquidity or ability to service debt obligations), but each provides
	additional information for evaluating our ability to make the Minimum Quarterly Distribution.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	33
</P>

	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</TD>

<TR STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:9PT">
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:1.00EM; TEXT-INDENT:-1.00EM; FONT-SIZE:9PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	(Increase) / decrease in the fair value of derivative instruments
</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(a)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA (Earnings from continuing operations before net interest expense, income taxes, depreciation and amortization) and Adjusted EBITDA (Earnings from continuing operations before net interest expense, income taxes,
	depreciation and amortization, (increase) decrease in the fair value of derivatives, multiemployer pension plan withdrawal charge, gain or loss on debt redemption, goodwill impairment, and other
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-operating
</FONT>
	charges) are
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-GAAP
</FONT>
	financial measures that are used as supplemental financial measures by management and external users of our financial statements, such as
	investors, commercial banks and research analysts, to assess:
</TD>

	&nbsp;

	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	our compliance with certain financial covenants included in our debt agreements;

	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	our financial performance without regard to financing methods, capital structure, income taxes or historical cost basis;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	our operating performance and return on invested capital compared to those of other companies in the retail distribution of refined petroleum products, without regard to financing methods and capital structure;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

</TD>

	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	our ability to generate cash sufficient to pay interest on our indebtedness and to make distributions to our partners; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	the viability of acquisitions and capital expenditure projects and the overall rates of return of alternative investment opportunities.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The method of calculating Adjusted EBITDA may not be consistent with that of other companies, and EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA both have limitations as
	analytical tools and so should not be viewed in isolation and should be viewed in conjunction with measurements that are computed in accordance with GAAP. Some of the limitations of EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA are:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect our cash used for capital expenditures;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Although depreciation and amortization are
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	charges, the assets being depreciated or amortized often will have to be replaced and EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect
	the cash requirements for such replacements;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect changes in, or cash requirements for, our working capital requirements;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect the cash necessary to make payments of interest or principal on our indebtedness; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect the cash required to pay taxes.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	Fiscal Year Ended September&nbsp;30, 2015
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	Compared to Fiscal Year Ended September&nbsp;30, 2014
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Volume
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, retail volume of
	home heating oil and propane sold increased by 21.8&nbsp;million gallons, or 6.1%, to 382.8&nbsp;million gallons, compared to 361.0&nbsp;million gallons for fiscal 2014. For those locations where the Partnership had existing operations during both
	periods, which we sometimes refer to as the &#147;base business&#148; (i.e., excluding acquisitions), temperatures (measured on a heating degree day basis) for fiscal 2015 were approximately equal to fiscal 2014 but 5.0% colder than normal, as
	reported by NOAA. For fiscal 2015, net customer attrition for the base business was 1.8%. Due to various reasons, we believe that our customers are adopting conservation measures to use less of our products. The impact of any such conservation,
	along with
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	any&nbsp;period-to-period&nbsp;differences
</FONT>
</FONT>
	in delivery scheduling, the timing of accounts added or lost during the fiscal years, equipment efficiency and
	other volume variances not otherwise described, are also included in the chart under the heading &#147;Other.&#148; An analysis of the change in the retail volume of home heating oil and propane, which is based on management&#146;s estimates,
	sampling and other mathematical calculations and certain assumptions, is found below:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

</P>
</TD>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Partnership has experienced a shift from our variable pricing plans to our price-protected plans as new
	customers and existing customers seek surety of price, which may impact our weighted average per gallon margins in the future.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Volume of
	other petroleum products sold increased by 15.5&nbsp;million gallons, or 18.0%, to 101.4&nbsp;million gallons for fiscal 2015, compared to 85.9&nbsp;million gallons for fiscal 2014, largely due to the additional volume from acquisitions of
	21.1&nbsp;million gallons, partially offset by a decline in the base business of 5.6&nbsp;million gallons.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Product Sales
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, product sales decreased $0.3&nbsp;billion, or 17.5%, to $1.4&nbsp;billion, compared to $1.7&nbsp;billion for fiscal 2014, as
	the impact from an increase in total volume of 8.4% and higher per gallon gross profit margins was more than offset by a decline in wholesale product costs of $1.0006 per gallon, or 33.1%.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	35
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage36"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Installations and Services Sales
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, installation and service sales increased $15.5&nbsp;million, or 6.8%, to $242.7&nbsp;million, compared to $227.3&nbsp;million
	for fiscal 2014, primarily due to additional revenue from acquisitions of $10.8&nbsp;million and an increase in the base business of $4.7&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Cost of Product
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, cost of
	product decreased $0.371&nbsp;billion, or 27.6%, to $0.978&nbsp;billion, compared to $1.349&nbsp;billion for fiscal 2014, as an increase in total volume of 8.4% was more than offset by a 33.1% decline, or $1.0006 per gallon, in wholesale product
	costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Gross Profit&#151;Product
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The table below calculates the Partnership&#146;s per gallon margins and reconciles product gross profit for home heating oil and propane and
	other petroleum products. We believe the change in home heating oil and propane margins should be evaluated before the effects of unrealized increases or decreases in the fair value of derivative instruments, as we believe that realized per gallon
	margins should not include the impact of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	changes in the market value of hedges before the settlement of the underlying transaction. On that basis, home heating oil and propane margins for fiscal 2015
	increased by $0.1058 per gallon, or 10.6%, to $1.1062 per gallon, from $1.0004 per gallon during fiscal 2014, due in part to the impact of the Griffith acquisition and primarily due to an increase in the base business as home heating oil and propane
	margins increased $0.0938 per gallon or 9.4%. In the previous five fiscal years, on average, our home heating oil and propane margins have increased by $0.0204 per gallon annually. The expansion of the Partnership&#146;s margins during fiscal 2015
	is in excess of the historical average by $0.0734 per gallon in the base business. The Partnership was able to expand its per gallon margins due to the precipitous decline in per gallon wholesale product costs. In addition, numerous snow storms and
	the intensity of the winter weather conditions experienced during the second quarter of fiscal 2015, drove an increase in operating and service costs and necessitated an increase in per gallon margins to help defray these additional operating
	expenses. Going forward, the Partnership cannot guarantee that the per gallon margins achieved during fiscal 2015 are sustainable and anticipates that per gallon margins will contract. Product sales and cost of product include the wholesale cost of
	home heating oil, propane, other petroleum products and liquidated damages billings.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" NOWRAP>
<P STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; BORDER-BOTTOM:1.00PT SOLID #000000; WIDTH:90.55PT; FONT-SIZE:8PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Other Petroleum Products
</B>
</P>

<A NAME="eolPage37"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, total product gross profit increased by $69.0&nbsp;million to
	$454.0&nbsp;million, compared to $385.0&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014, due to an increase in home heating oil and propane volume ($21.9 million), the impact of higher home heating oil and propane margins ($40.5 million), and the additional gross
	profit from other petroleum products ($6.5 million).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Cost of Installations and Services
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, cost of installations and services increased by $20.1&nbsp;million, or 9.8%, to $225.9&nbsp;million, compared to
	$205.8&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014, reflecting a $9.7&nbsp;million increase related to acquisitions and $10.4&nbsp;million higher expenses in our base business.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Installation costs for fiscal 2015, rose by $2.8&nbsp;million, or 4.0%, to $73.2&nbsp;million, compared to $70.4&nbsp;million in installation
	costs for fiscal 2014 due to acquisitions. Installation costs as a percentage of installation sales for fiscal 2015 and fiscal 2014 were 84.2% and 85.3%, respectively. Service expenses increased to $152.8&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015, or 98.1% of
	service sales, versus $135.5&nbsp;million, or 93.6% of service sales, for fiscal 2014. The higher service expense of $17.3&nbsp;million reflects an increase related to acquisitions of $6.6&nbsp;million and an increase in the base business of
	$10.6&nbsp;million, or 7.9%. In addition to normal inflationary pressures on service expenses, the 5.8% colder temperatures experienced in the second quarter of fiscal 2015 drove an increase in the amount of service work required to ensure our
	customers&#146; heating systems were operational. The numerous snow storms in certain areas of our footprint hampered productivity and also drove an increase in service costs as the additional service work was performed at premium labor rates. In
	addition, the Partnership&#146;s expansion of its service offerings resulted in an increase in service costs. We experienced a combined gross profit from service and installation of $16.7&nbsp;million for fiscal 2015, compared to a combined gross
	profit of $21.4&nbsp;million fiscal 2014. Management views the service and installation department on a combined basis because many overhead functions and direct expenses such as service technician time cannot be separated or precisely allocated to
	either service or installation billings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	(Increase) / Decrease in the Fair Value of Derivative Instruments
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During fiscal 2015, the change in the fair value of derivative instruments resulted in a $4.2&nbsp;million charge due to the expiration of
	certain hedged positions (a $12.1&nbsp;million credit) and a decrease in the market value for unexpired hedges (a $16.3&nbsp;million charge).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During fiscal 2014, the change in the fair value of derivative instruments resulted in a $6.6&nbsp;million charge due to the expiration of
	certain hedged positions (a $5.6&nbsp;million credit) and a decrease in the market value for unexpired hedges (a $12.2&nbsp;million charge).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Delivery
	and Branch Expenses
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, delivery and branch expense increased $26.4&nbsp;million, or 9.3%, to $309.0&nbsp;million,
	compared to $282.6&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014, as a result of an increase related to acquisitions of $19.3&nbsp;million and an increase in the base business of $7.1&nbsp;million due in part to the colder temperatures experienced during the second
	quarter of fiscal 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On a cents per gallon basis, delivery and branch expenses for fiscal 2015, increased slightly to $0.6529 compared
	to $0.6514 for fiscal 2014. The additional volume delivered during the second fiscal quarter (due to colder weather) was at premium labor rates, and the numerous snow storms created operational inefficiencies which also led to a higher than expected
	cents per gallon of delivery and branch expenses. This was offset by lower per gallon operating expense from acquisitions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Depreciation and
	Amortization
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, depreciation and amortization expense increased by $3.3&nbsp;million, or 15.2%, to $24.9&nbsp;million,
	compared to $21.6&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014 largely due to fiscal 2014 and 2015 acquisitions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	General and Administrative Expenses
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, general and administrative expenses increased $3.3&nbsp;million, or 14.7&nbsp;%, to $25.9&nbsp;million, from
	$22.6&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014, as a result of an increase in profit sharing expense of $1.8&nbsp;million and $1.5&nbsp;million in legal and professional fees largely due to a debt refinancing abandoned by the Partnership in the first quarter of
	fiscal 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Partnership accrues approximately 6% of Adjusted EBITDA as defined in the profit sharing plan for distribution to its
	employees, and this amount is payable when the Partnership achieves Adjusted EBITDA of at least 70% of the amount budgeted. The dollar amount of the profit sharing pool is subject to increases and decreases in line with increases and decreases in
	Adjusted EBITDA.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	37
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage38"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Multiemployer Pension Plan Withdrawal Charge
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In fiscal 2015, we entered into an agreement among certain Star subsidiaries and the New England Teamsters and Trucking Industry Pension Fund
	(the &#147;NETTI Fund&#148;), a multiemployer pension plan in which such Star subsidiaries participate, providing for Star&#146;s participating subsidiaries to withdraw from the NETTI Fund&#146;s original employer pool and enter the NETTI
	Fund&#146;s new employer pool. The withdrawal from the original employer pool triggered an undiscounted withdrawal obligation of $48.0&nbsp;million to be paid in equal monthly installments over 30 years, or $1.6&nbsp;million per year. The estimated
	annual
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	after-tax
</FONT>
	cash impact of entering into this agreement is $0.9&nbsp;million. In September 2015, we recorded a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	charge in order to establish a withdrawal
	obligation of approximately $17.8&nbsp;million on the consolidated balance sheet, representing the present value of the $48.0&nbsp;million future payment obligation at a discount rate of 8.22%. We also recorded a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	deferred tax benefit from the agreement of approximately $7.0&nbsp;million. We believe the new agreement reduces long-term financial risk for the Partnership.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Finance Charge Income
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015,
	finance charge income decreased $2.1&nbsp;million to $4.8&nbsp;million, compared to $6.9&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014. The decline in the wholesale cost of product led to lower retail selling prices and thus a decline in accounts receivable balances
	subject to a finance charge.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Interest Expense, Net
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, interest expense decreased $2.8&nbsp;million, or 16.6&nbsp;%, to $14.1&nbsp;million compared to $16.9&nbsp;million for fiscal
	2014 primarily due in part to a decrease in average working capital borrowings of $68.7&nbsp;million. Working capital borrowings were lower due to lower wholesale product costs. In September 2015, the Partnership redeemed its $125.0&nbsp;million
	principal amount of 8.875% Senior Notes outstanding due 2017 with proceeds from a new, five year $100.0&nbsp;million bank term-loan and cash. This refinancing resulted in a reduction of interest expense of $0.6&nbsp;million due to lower variable
	rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Amortization of Debt Issuance Costs
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, amortization of debt issuance costs increased by $0.2&nbsp;million to $1.8&nbsp;million compared to $1.6&nbsp;million for
	fiscal 2014 largely due to the Partnership&#146;s debt refinancing.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Loss on Debt Redemption
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In September 2015, the Partnership redeemed all its $125.0&nbsp;million principal amount of 8.875% Senior Notes due 2017, at the then current
	redemption price of $104.438 per $100 of principal plus accrued interest. The Partnership recorded a loss of $7.3&nbsp;million on this transaction, resulting from the $5.5&nbsp;million redemption price premium, the related write-offs of
	$1.5&nbsp;million in unamortized deferred charges, and $0.3&nbsp;million of unamortized debt discount.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Income Tax Expense
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, income tax expense increased by $7.5&nbsp;million to $32.8&nbsp;million from $25.3&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014, due to an
	increase in pretax income of $9.0&nbsp;million as well as an increase in the effective income tax rate. The Partnership&#146;s effective tax rate was 46.6% for fiscal 2015 versus 41.2% for fiscal 2014. The loss on the redemption of the
	Partnership&#146;s $125.0&nbsp;million principal amount of 8.875% Senior Notes due 2017 was not deductible at the Partnership&#146;s corporate subsidiaries which drove the increase in the effective tax rate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Net Income
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015, net income
	increased $1.5&nbsp;million to $37.6&nbsp;million, from $36.1&nbsp;million for fiscal 2014, as the increase in pretax income of $9.0&nbsp;million was greater than the increase in income tax expense of $7.5&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Adjusted EBITDA
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For fiscal 2015,
	Adjusted EBITDA increased by $32.5&nbsp;million, or 30.0&nbsp;%, to $140.5&nbsp;million as the impact of higher home heating oil and propane per gallon margins and acquisitions more than offset higher operating and service costs largely attributable
	to colder temperatures and numerous snow storms during the second quarter of fiscal 2015 and the volume decline in the base business attributable to net customer attrition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	38
</P>

</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA should not be considered as an alternative to net income (as an
	indicator of operating performance) or as an alternative to cash flow (as a measure of liquidity or ability to service debt obligations), but provides additional information for evaluating our ability to make the Minimum Quarterly Distribution.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA are calculated as follows:
</P>

</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(a)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA (Earnings from continuing operations before net interest expense, income taxes, depreciation and amortization) and Adjusted EBITDA (Earnings from continuing operations before net interest expense, income taxes,
	depreciation and amortization, (increase) decrease in the fair value of derivatives, multiemployer pension plan withdrawal charge, gain or loss on debt redemption, goodwill impairment, and other
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-operating
</FONT>
	charges) are
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-GAAP
</FONT>
	financial measures that are used as supplemental financial measures by management and external users of our financial statements, such as
	investors, commercial banks and research analysts, to assess:
</TD>

	&nbsp;

	&nbsp;
</TD>

	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	our compliance with certain financial covenants included in our debt agreements;

</TR>

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	our financial performance without regard to financing methods, capital structure, income taxes or historical cost basis;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	our operating performance and return on invested capital compared to those of other companies in the retail distribution of refined petroleum products, without regard to financing methods and capital structure;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;

	our ability to generate cash sufficient to pay interest on our indebtedness and to make distributions to our partners; and
</TD>

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	the viability of acquisitions and capital expenditure projects and the overall rates of return of alternative investment opportunities.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	39

<A NAME="eolPage40"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The method of calculating Adjusted EBITDA may not be consistent with that of other companies, and
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA both have limitations as analytical tools and so should not be viewed in isolation and should be viewed in conjunction with measurements that are computed in accordance with GAAP. Some of the limitations of EBITDA and
	Adjusted EBITDA are:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect our cash used for capital expenditures;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Although depreciation and amortization are
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-cash
</FONT>
	charges, the assets being depreciated or amortized often will have to be replaced and EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect
	the cash requirements for such replacements;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect changes in, or cash requirements for, our working capital requirements;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect the cash necessary to make payments of interest or principal on our indebtedness; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA do not reflect the cash required to pay taxes.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	DISCUSSION OF CASH FLOWS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We use the indirect method to prepare our Consolidated Statements of Cash Flows. Under this method, we reconcile net income to cash
	flows provided by operating activities by adjusting net income for those items that impact net income but may not result in actual cash receipts or payment during the period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Operating Activities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Due to the seasonal
	nature of our business, cash is generally used in operations during the winter (our first and second fiscal quarters) as we require additional working capital to support the high volume of sales during this period, and cash is generally provided by
	operating activities during the spring and summer (our third and fourth quarters) when customer payments exceed the cost of deliveries.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During fiscal 2016, cash provided by operating activities decreased by $34.9&nbsp;million to $102.0&nbsp;million, compared to
	$136.9&nbsp;million of cash provided by operating activities during fiscal 2015, largely due to a $29.7&nbsp;million decrease in cash generated from operations and an unfavorable change in accounts receivable of $16.7&nbsp;million (including
	customer credit balances). The impact of the significantly warmer weather drove the reduction in cash flow from operating activities and the change in accounts receivable. Cash flow from operations was positively impacted by a change in other assets
	and liabilities of $11.5&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During fiscal 2015, cash provided by operating activities increased by $41.7&nbsp;million to
	$136.9&nbsp;million, compared to $95.2&nbsp;million of cash provided by operating activities during fiscal 2014, as a $19.2&nbsp;million increase in cash generated from operations and a favorable change in accounts receivable of $23.8&nbsp;million
	(including customer credit balances) were reduced by changes in other assets and liabilities of $1.3&nbsp;million. Cash flow from operating activities increased largely due to the impact of acquisitions and accounts receivable were favorably
	impacted by a decline in wholesale product costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Investing Activities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our capital expenditures for fiscal 2016 totaled $10.1&nbsp;million, as we invested in computer hardware and software ($2.8 million),
	refurbished certain physical plants ($1.3 million), expanded our propane operations ($2.9 million) and made additions to our fleet and other equipment ($3.1 million). We also completed four acquisitions for $9.8&nbsp;million and allocated
	$7.4&nbsp;million of the gross purchase price to intangible assets, $2.5&nbsp;million to fixed assets and reduced working capital by $0.1&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our capital expenditures for fiscal 2015 totaled $9.6&nbsp;million, as we invested in computer hardware and software ($2.9 million),
	refurbished certain physical plants ($1.4 million), expanded our propane operations ($2.7 million) and made additions to our fleet and other equipment ($2.6 million). We also completed two acquisitions for $21.1&nbsp;million and allocated
	$20.7&nbsp;million of the gross purchase price to intangible assets, $2.5&nbsp;million to fixed assets and reduced working capital by $2.1&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Financing Activities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During fiscal 2016,
	we paid distributions of $22.6&nbsp;million to our common unit holders, $0.5&nbsp;million to our general partner (including $0.4&nbsp;million of incentive distributions as provided in our Partnership Agreement) and repaid $7.5&nbsp;million of our
	term-loan. We also repurchased 1.4&nbsp;million common units for $12.0&nbsp;million in connection with our unit repurchase plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	40
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage41"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During fiscal 2015, we borrowed $12.3&nbsp;million under our credit facility and repaid
	$12.3&nbsp;million during the period. We also paid distributions of $21.3&nbsp;million to our common unit holders, $0.4&nbsp;million to our general partner (including $0.3&nbsp;million of incentive distributions as provided in our Partnership
	Agreement). In September 2015, the Partnership redeemed its $125.0&nbsp;million principal amount of 8.875% Senior Notes due 2017 with the proceeds of a $100.0&nbsp;million bank term-loan and cash. We paid a total of $8.0&nbsp;million in call
	premiums and bank fees relating to this transaction.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	FINANCING AND SOURCES OF LIQUIDITY
</B>
</P>
</EFX_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS>
<EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
<A NAME="FIS_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Liquidity and Capital Resources
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our
	primary uses of liquidity are to provide funds for our working capital, capital expenditures, distributions on our units, acquisitions and unit repurchases. Our ability to provide funds for such uses depends on our future performance, which will be
	subject to prevailing economic, financial, business and weather conditions, the ability to pass on the full impact of high product costs to customers, the effects of high net customer attrition, conservation and other factors. Capital requirements,
	at least in the near term, are expected to be provided by cash flows from operating activities, cash on hand as of September&nbsp;30, 2016 ($139.2 million) or a combination thereof. To the extent future capital requirements exceed cash on hand plus
	cash flows from operating activities, we anticipate that working capital will be financed by our revolving credit facility, as discussed below, and repaid from subsequent seasonal reductions in inventory and accounts receivable. As of
	September&nbsp;30, 2016, we had no borrowings under our revolving credit facility and $50.6&nbsp;million in letters of credit were outstanding, primarily for current and future insurance reserves, and our ability to borrow was reduced by
	$0.3&nbsp;million to secure hedges with the bank group.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under the terms of the third amended and restated credit agreement, we must
	maintain at all times Availability (borrowing base less amounts borrowed and letters of credit issued) of 12.5% of the maximum facility size and a fixed charge coverage ratio of not less than 1.1. While the term-loan is outstanding we must maintain
	a senior secured leverage ratio that at any time cannot be more than 3.0 as calculated during the quarters ending June or September, and at any time no more than 4.5 as calculated during the quarters ending December or March. As of
	September&nbsp;30, 2016, Availability, as defined in the credit agreement, was $163.4&nbsp;million, and we were in compliance with the fixed charge coverage ratio and senior secured leverage ratio.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Maintenance capital expenditures for fiscal 2017 are estimated to be approximately $9.9&nbsp;million, excluding the capital requirements for
	leased fleet. In addition, we plan to invest an additional $4.0&nbsp;million in our propane operations including several
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	start-up
</FONT>
	operations. Distributions for fiscal 2017, at the current quarterly level of
	$0.1025 per unit, would result in an aggregate of approximately $22.9&nbsp;million to common unit holders, $0.5&nbsp;million to our general partner (including $0.4&nbsp;million of incentive distribution as provided for in our Partnership Agreement)
	and $0.4&nbsp;million to management pursuant to the management incentive compensation plan which provides for certain members of management to receive incentive distributions that would otherwise be payable to the general partner. Under the terms of
	our credit facility, our term-loan is repayable in quarterly payments of $2.5&nbsp;million, or $10&nbsp;million annually, and the Partnership expects to make an additional term-loan payment of $6.2&nbsp;million in December 2016 due to Excess Cash
	Flow (as defined in the credit agreement) generated for fiscal 2016. As a result of the NETTI Fund agreement, the Partnership will be paying $1.6&nbsp;million to the fund in fiscal 2017. We also intend to contribute $2.0&nbsp;million into the
	Partnership&#146;s frozen pension plan and, continue to repurchase Common Units pursuant to our unit repurchase plan, and seek attractive acquisition opportunities within the Availability constraints of our credit agreement and funding resources.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	41

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	balance sheet.
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">

	purchase obligations are obligations we incur during the normal course of business, based on projected needs. The Partnership had no capital lease obligations as of

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Recent Accounting Pronouncements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In May 2014, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#147;FASB&#148;) issued Accounting Standards Update (&#147;ASU&#148;)
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2014-09,
</FONT>
	Revenue from Contracts with Customers, which requires an entity to recognize the amount of revenue to which it expects to be entitled for the transfer of promised goods or services to customers.
	This ASU will replace most existing revenue recognition guidance in GAAP when it becomes effective. This new guidance is effective for our annual reporting period beginning in the first quarter of fiscal 2019, with early adoption permitted beginning
	in the first quarter of fiscal 2018. The standard permits the use of either the retrospective or cumulative effect transition method. The Partnership is evaluating the effect that ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	2014-09
</FONT>
	will have on its
	consolidated financial statements and related disclosures. The Partnership has not yet selected a transition method nor has it determined the timing of adoption.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In April 2015, the FASB issued ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2015-03,
</FONT>
	Interest&#151;Imputation of Interest (Subtopic
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	835-30):
</FONT>
	Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs. The update requires debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying
	amount of the related debt liability instead of being presented as an asset. The update requires retrospective application and represents a change in accounting principle. The update is effective for our annual reporting period beginning in the
	first quarter of fiscal 2017, with early adoption permitted. The Partnership expects the impact of ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2015-03
</FONT>
	will be limited to the presentation of debt issuance cost on its balance sheet.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In July 2015, the FASB issued ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2015-11,
</FONT>
	Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory. The
	update changes the measurement principle for inventory from the lower of cost or market to the lower of cost and net realizable value. This new guidance is effective for our annual reporting period beginning in the first quarter of fiscal 2018, with
	early adoption permitted. The Partnership does not expect ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2015-11
</FONT>
	to have a material impact on its consolidated financial statements and related disclosures.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	42
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage43"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In September 2015, the FASB issued ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2015-16,
</FONT>
	Simplifying the Accounting for Measurement-Period Adjustments, which requires an acquiring entity to recognize adjustments to provisional amounts that are identified during the measurement period in the reporting period in which the adjustment
	amounts are determined. The acquiring entity is required to record, in the same period&#146;s financial statements, the effect on earnings of changes in depreciation, amortization, or other income effects, if any, as a result of the change to the
	provisional amounts, calculated as if the accounting had been completed at the acquisition date. In addition, the acquiring entity is to present separately on the face of its income statement or disclose in the notes the portion of the amount
	recorded in current-period earnings by line item that would have been recorded in previous reporting periods as if the adjustment to the provisional amounts had been recognized as of the acquisition date. This new guidance is effective for our
	annual reporting period beginning in the first quarter of fiscal 2017. The Partnership does not expect ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2015-16
</FONT>
	to have a material impact on its consolidated financial statements and related
	disclosures.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In November 2015, FASB issued ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	2015-17,
</FONT>
	Income Taxes&#151;Balance Sheet
	Classification of Deferred Taxes, which eliminates the requirement for companies to present deferred tax assets and liabilities as current and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-current
</FONT>
	in a classified balance sheet. Instead, companies are
	required to classify all deferred tax assets and liabilities as
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-current.
</FONT>
	The Partnership retrospectively adopted the ASU effective September&nbsp;30, 2016. As a result of the adoption, certain prior year
	balances changed to conform to the current year presentation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In February 2016, the FASB issued ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2016-02,
</FONT>
	Leases.&nbsp;The update requires all leases with a term greater than twelve months to be recognized on the balance sheet through a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	right-of-use
</FONT>
</FONT>
	asset and a lease liability and the disclosure of key information pertaining to leasing arrangements.&nbsp;This new guidance is effective for our annual reporting period beginning in the first
	quarter of fiscal 2020, with early adoption permitted.&nbsp;The Partnership is evaluating the effect that ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2016-02
</FONT>
	will have on its consolidated financial statements and related disclosures, but
	has not yet selected a transition method or determined the timing of adoption.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In June 2016, the FASB issued ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2016-13,
</FONT>
	Financial Instruments &#150; Credit Losses.&nbsp;The update broadens the information that an entity should consider in developing expected credit loss estimates, eliminates the probable initial
	recognition threshold, and allows for the immediate recognition of the full amount of expected credit losses.&nbsp;This new guidance is effective for our annual reporting period beginning in the first quarter of fiscal 2021, with early adoption
	permitted in the first quarter of fiscal 2020. The Partnership is evaluating the effect that ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2016-13
</FONT>
	will have on its consolidated financial statements and related disclosures, but has not yet
	determined the timing of adoption.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In August 2016, the FASB issued ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2016-15,
</FONT>
	Statement of Cash Flow (Topic 230): Classification of Certain Cash Receipts and Cash Payments. The update addresses the issues of debt prepayment or debt extinguishment costs, settlement of
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	zero-coupon
</FONT>
	debt
	instruments or other debt instruments with coupon interest rates that are insignificant in relation to the effective interest rate of the borrowing, contingent consideration payments made after a business combination, proceeds from the settlement of
	insurance claims, proceeds from the settlement of corporate owned life insurance policies, distributions received from equity method investees, beneficial interests in securitization transactions, and separately identifiable cash flows and
	application of the predominance principle. This new guidance is effective for our annual reporting period beginning in the first quarter of fiscal 2019, with early adoption permitted. The Partnership does not expect ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2016-15
</FONT>
	to have a material impact on its consolidated financial statements and related disclosures.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Critical Accounting Estimates
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The
	preparation of financial statements in conformity with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles requires management to establish accounting policies and make estimates and assumptions that affect reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the
	date of the Consolidated Financial Statements. The Partnership evaluates its policies and estimates on an
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	on-going
</FONT>
	basis. A change in any of these critical accounting estimates could have a material effect on
	the results of operations. The Partnership&#146;s Consolidated Financial Statements may differ based upon different estimates and assumptions. The Partnership&#146;s critical accounting estimates have been reviewed with the Audit Committee of the
	Board of Directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our significant accounting policies are discussed in Note 2 of the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements. We
	believe the following are our critical accounting policies and estimates:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We calculate amortization using the straight-line method over periods ranging from five to twenty years for intangible assets with finite
	useful lives based on historical statistics. We use amortization methods and determine asset values based on our best estimates using reasonable and supportable assumptions and projections. Key assumptions used to determine the value of these
	intangibles include projections of future customer attrition or growth rates, product margin increases, operating expenses, our cost of
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	43
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage44"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D260533D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	capital, and corporate income tax rates. For significant acquisitions we may engage a third party valuation firm to assist in the valuation of intangible assets of that acquisition. We assess the
	useful lives of intangible assets based on the estimated period over which we will receive benefit from such intangible assets such as historical evidence regarding customer churn rate. In some cases, the estimated useful lives are based on
	contractual terms. At September&nbsp;30, 2016, we had $97.7&nbsp;million of net intangible assets subject to amortization. If lives were shortened by one year, we estimate that amortization for these assets for fiscal 2016 would have increased by
	approximately $2.7&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	FASB ASC
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	350-10-05,
</FONT>
</FONT>
	Intangibles-Goodwill and Other, requires goodwill to be assessed at least annually for impairment. The Partnership has one reporting segment and performs its annual assessment at the end of August. As provided for by the standard, we performed
	qualitative assessments (commonly referred to as Step 0) to evaluate whether it is
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	more-likely-than-not
</FONT>
	(a likelihood that is more than 50%) that goodwill has been impaired, as a basis to determine whether it
	is necessary to perform the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	two-step
</FONT>
	quantitative impairment test. The Partnership&#146;s qualitative assessment included a review of factors such as our reporting segment&#146;s market value compared to its
	carrying value, our short-term and long-term unit price performance, our planned overall business strategy compared to recent financial results, as well as macroeconomic conditions, industry and market considerations, cost factors, and other
	relevant Partnership-specific events. In considering the totality of the qualitative factors assessed, based on the weight of evidence it was determined that it was not
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	more-likely-than-not
</FONT>
	that goodwill was
	impaired as of August&nbsp;31, 2016, and as such it was determined that further goodwill testing was not necessary.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Intangible assets
	with finite lives must be assessed for impairment whenever changes in circumstances indicate that the assets may be impaired. The assessment for impairment requires estimates of future cash flows related to the intangible asset. To the extent the
	carrying value of the assets exceeds its future undiscounted cash flows, an impairment loss is recorded based on the fair value of the asset.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Fair
	Values of Derivatives
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	FASB ASC
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	815-10-05,
</FONT>
</FONT>
	Derivatives
	and Hedging, requires that derivative instruments be recorded at fair value and included in the consolidated balance sheet as assets or liabilities. The Partnership has elected not to designate its derivative instruments as hedging instruments under
	this guidance, and the change in fair value of the derivative instruments are recognized in our statement of operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We have
	established the fair value of our derivative instruments using estimates determined by our counterparties and subsequently evaluated them internally using established index prices and other sources. These values are based upon, among other things,
	future prices, volatility,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	time-to-maturity
</FONT>
</FONT>
	value and credit risk. The estimate of fair value we report in our financial statements changes as these estimates are
	revised to reflect actual results, changes in market conditions, or other factors, many of which are beyond our control.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Insurance Reserves
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We currently self-insure a portion of workers&#146; compensation, auto and general liability claims. We establish reserves based upon
	expectations as to what our ultimate liability may be for outstanding claims using developmental factors based upon historical claim experience, supplemented by a third-party actuary. We periodically evaluate the potential for changes in loss
	estimates with the support of qualified actuaries. As of September&nbsp;30, 2016, we had approximately $64.1&nbsp;million of net insurance reserves. The ultimate resolution of these claims could differ materially from the assumptions used to
	calculate the reserves, which could have a material adverse effect on results of operations.
</P>

<EFX_MARKET_RISK>
<A NAME="FIS_MARKET_RISK"></A>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="9%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
<A NAME="D260533D10K_HTM_TX260533_12">
</A>
	ITEM&nbsp;7A.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	QUANTITATIVE AND QUALITATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET RISK
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We are exposed to interest
	rate risk primarily through our bank credit facilities. We utilize these borrowings to meet our working capital needs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At
	September&nbsp;30, 2016, we had outstanding borrowings totaling $92.5&nbsp;million, which are subject to variable interest rates under our credit agreement. In the event that interest rates associated with this facility were to increase 100 basis
	points, the after tax impact on annual future cash flows would be a decrease of $0.6&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We regularly use derivative financial
	instruments to manage our exposure to market risk related to changes in the current and future market price of home heating oil. The value of market sensitive derivative instruments is subject to change as a result of movements in market prices.
	Sensitivity analysis is a technique used to evaluate the impact of hypothetical market value changes. Based on a hypothetical ten percent increase in the cost of product at September&nbsp;30, 2016, the potential impact on our hedging activity would
	be to increase the fair market value of these outstanding derivatives by $12.2&nbsp;million to a fair market value of $14.7&nbsp;million; and conversely a hypothetical ten percent decrease in the cost of product would decrease the fair market value
	of these outstanding derivatives by $6.1&nbsp;million to a negative fair market value of $3.6&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	44
</P>
